introduction.p:
A partition of integer n is a multiset of positive integers whose sum is n. Here are three symbols we use for counting integer partitions:

\begin{array}{rcl}
p(n,k) & = & \mbox{# partitions of } n \mbox{ into } k \mbox{ parts} \\
\\
p_k(n) & = &  \mbox{# partitions of } n \mbox{ into at most } k \mbox{ parts} \\
&=& \displaystyle{\sum_{i=1}^k p(n,i)}\\
\\
p(n) & = &  \mbox{# partitions of } n \mbox{ into any number of parts}  \\
&=& \displaystyle{\sum_{i=1}^n p(n,i)}
\end{array}

statement.p:
In this problem, you will investigate the equivalence

p_k(n) =
p(n+k,k)







 Interpret each side of this equality.









 LHS = Number of partitions of n into at most k parts






 RHS = Number of partitions of n+k into exactly k parts.












 Verify this result for n=5 and k=3. In other words, find all partitions of both types. You will find that there are equal numbers of these partitions.




